The Kepler-60 Exoplanetary System


Overview

Kepler-60 is a star with 1.04 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.26 times its radius. It is located NaN light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 5 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

Kepler-60 is known to have undefined exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the Kepler-60 system


Kepler-60 b

Kepler-60 b was discovered by the undefined observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.07 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of Kepler-60 b is 4.1912400000000005 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-60 b is 1.71 that of Earth. At 4.1912400000000005 Earth masses, Kepler-60 b is a so called Super Earth. Super Earths could be terrestrial worlds like Earth, but they could also be ocean worlds or terrestrial worlds wrapped in a substantial atmosphere, in which case some refer to them as Mini Neptunes. No Super Earths are known to exist in our solar system, but if it exists, the so-called Planet Nine could very well be a super Earth, as it is hypothesized to have a mass between five and ten Earth masses.
